---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro'
import ProductCard from '../components/ProductCard.astro'
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Hurricane Home Protection Guide"
  description="Learn how to protect your home from hurricanes. Covers roof hardening, storm shutters, flood insurance, generators, and evacuation planning. Expert guides and product recommendations."
>

  <!-- ── Hero ── -->
  <section class="threat-hero hurricane-hero">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="threat-hero-inner">
        <p class="threat-eyebrow">🌀 Hurricane Preparedness</p>
        <h1>How to Protect Your Home from Hurricanes</h1>
        <p class="threat-sub">
          Hurricanes don't give you much warning. The decisions that protect your home 
          are made weeks before landfall — not hours before. Here's everything you need to know.
        </p>
        <div class="hero-ctas">
          <a href="#checklist" class="btn btn-primary">Get the Free Checklist</a>
          <a href="#products" class="btn btn-secondary">See Recommended Products</a>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ── Quick stats bar ── -->
  <div class="stats-bar">
    <div class="container stats-grid">
      <div class="stat">
        <strong>June 1 – Nov 30</strong>
        <span>Atlantic hurricane season</span>
      </div>
      <div class="stat">
        <strong>74+ mph</strong>
        <span>Minimum Category 1 wind speed</span>
      </div>
      <div class="stat">
        <strong>Storm surge</strong>
        <span>Leading cause of hurricane deaths</span>
      </div>
      <div class="stat">
        <strong>30 days</strong>
        <span>NFIP flood insurance waiting period</span>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ── Main content ── -->
  <div class="container content-layout">

    <!-- ── Left: Article content ── -->
    <article class="article-body">

      <h2>Understanding the Risks</h2>
      <p>
        A hurricane is a tropical storm with sustained winds of at least 74 mph. They bring 
        a dangerous combination of high winds, heavy rainfall, and storm surge — the wall of 
        ocean water pushed inland by the storm — that can overwhelm coastal and inland homes 
        alike. Hurricane season peaks in August and September, but storms can form any time 
        between June and November.
      </p>

      <div class="risk-cards">
        <div class="risk-card">
          <div class="risk-icon">🌊</div>
          <h3>Storm Surge</h3>
          <p>The leading cause of hurricane deaths. Can flood ground floors with several feet of water in minutes. Extends miles inland.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="risk-card">
          <div class="risk-icon">💨</div>
          <h3>Wind Damage</h3>
          <p>Strips roofing, shatters windows, and collapses structures — even miles from the coast. Debris becomes lethal projectiles.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="risk-card">
          <div class="risk-icon">⚡</div>
          <h3>Power Outages</h3>
          <p>Extended outages lasting days or weeks are the norm after a major storm. Sump pumps stop, food spoils, medical equipment fails.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="risk-card">
          <div class="risk-icon">🍄</div>
          <h3>Flooding & Mold</h3>
          <p>Mold begins growing within 24–48 hours of water intrusion. A flooded home can be uninhabitable for months.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- ── Section 1: Backup Power ── -->
      <h2 id="power">1. Backup Power Is Non-Negotiable</h2>
      <p>
        Power outages after hurricanes routinely last one to three weeks. Without power, your 
        sump pump won't run, your food will spoil, your AC won't work in the August heat, and 
        if anyone in your home depends on medical equipment — the stakes are even higher.
      </p>
      <p>
        A generator is the single most impactful purchase most homeowners can make for hurricane 
        preparedness. The key decisions are <strong>portable vs. standby</strong> and 
        <strong>what size you actually need</strong>.
      </p>

      <div class="callout callout-tip">
        <strong>⚠️ Critical timing:</strong> Generators sell out within hours of a named storm 
        forming. Buy before hurricane season — not when a storm is in the forecast.
      </div>

      <h3>Portable Generators (Most Homeowners)</h3>
      <p>
        A 5,000–7,500 watt portable generator runs your refrigerator, window AC unit, fans, 
        phone chargers, and lights. It requires manual setup and refueling every 8–12 hours, 
        but costs a fraction of a standby unit. Budget $600–$1,500 for a quality portable.
      </p>

      <h3>Standby Generators (Whole-Home Solution)</h3>
      <p>
        A whole-home standby generator runs on natural gas or propane, starts automatically 
        when power goes out, and can power your entire house indefinitely. They require 
        professional installation and cost $5,000–$15,000 installed, but for homeowners in 
        high-risk areas they're worth serious consideration.
      </p>

      <div class="callout callout-warning">
        <strong>🚨 Safety:</strong> NEVER run a generator inside your home, garage, or carport. 
        Carbon monoxide is colorless and odorless and kills within minutes. Position at least 
        20 feet from any window or door.
      </div>

      <div class="product-section" id="products">
        <h3>Recommended Generators</h3>
        <div class="product-grid">
          <ProductCard
            name="Honda EU2200i Portable Inverter Generator"
            asin="B077K3BKPV"
            price="$1,099"
            store="amazon"
            badge="Editor's Pick"
            desc="Whisper-quiet, fuel-efficient, and reliable. The gold standard for portable power. Runs 8+ hours on 1 gallon of fuel."
          />
          <ProductCard
            name="Champion 7500-Watt Dual Fuel Generator"
            asin="B07FDQJRBT"
            price="$729"
            store="amazon"
            badge="Best Value"
            desc="Runs on gasoline or propane. 7,500 watts handles refrigerator, AC, and essential circuits. Electric start included."
          />
          <ProductCard
            name="EcoFlow DELTA Pro Portable Power Station"
            asin="B09GXTD9KH"
            price="$2,799"
            store="amazon"
            desc="No fuel, no fumes — safe to use indoors. 3,600Wh capacity. Expandable and charges via solar. Best for apartments or HOA communities."
          />
        </div>
        <p class="product-note">→ See our complete <a href="/generators">Generator Buying Guide</a> for full reviews, sizing calculator, and installation tips.</p>
      </div>

      <!-- ── Section 2: Flood ── -->
      <h2 id="flood">2. Know Your Flood Risk and Act on It</h2>
      <p>
        Even homes miles from the coast can flood during a hurricane. Storm surge pushes ocean 
        water inland, heavy rainfall overwhelms drainage systems, and rivers rise well above 
        normal levels. The first step is understanding your specific risk.
      </p>

      <div class="action-steps">
        <div class="action-step">
          <div class="step-num">1</div>
          <div>
            <strong>Look up your FEMA flood zone</strong>
            <p>Go to <a href="https://msc.fema.gov" target="_blank" rel="noopener">msc.fema.gov</a> and enter your address. This tells you your official flood designation and your Base Flood Elevation.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="action-step">
          <div class="step-num">2</div>
          <div>
            <strong>Buy flood insurance now — not when a storm forms</strong>
            <p>Your homeowner's insurance policy does NOT cover flooding under any circumstances. NFIP flood insurance has a mandatory 30-day waiting period before it takes effect.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="action-step">
          <div class="step-num">3</div>
          <div>
            <strong>Install flood protection at entry points</strong>
            <p>Door dam flood shields and sandbags at all ground-level doors and windows can prevent significant water intrusion during a surge event.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="action-step">
          <div class="step-num">4</div>
          <div>
            <strong>Test your sump pump and install a battery backup</strong>
            <p>Your sump pump is useless without power — and floods cause power outages. A battery backup sump pump runs automatically when power fails.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="product-grid" style="margin-top: 24px;">
        <ProductCard
          name="Wayne ESP25 Battery Backup Sump Pump"
          asin="B000BQOTIA"
          price="$189"
          store="amazon"
          badge="Top Rated"
          desc="Activates automatically when power fails or primary pump is overwhelmed. Pumps 2,300 gallons/hour. Standard 12V battery (not included)."
        />
        <ProductCard
          name="FLOODGATE Door Flood Barrier"
          asin="B08FKZSS7Q"
          price="$129"
          store="amazon"
          desc="Reusable door flood shield. Deploys in minutes, fits standard door frames, holds back up to 18 inches of water. Far superior to sandbags."
        />
      </div>

      <p class="product-note">→ See our full <a href="/flood-protection-products">Flood Protection Products Guide</a> for sump pumps, flood barriers, and waterproofing.</p>

      <!-- ── Section 3: Windows & Shutters ── -->
      <h2 id="windows">3. Secure Your Windows and Doors</h2>
      <p>
        Once wind breaches your home's envelope — through a window, door, or garage door — 
        internal pressure builds rapidly and can lift your roof off. Impact-resistant windows 
        and hurricane shutters are the most effective permanent solution. If you haven't 
        installed those, you need a plan before hurricane season.
      </p>

      <div class="callout callout-info">
        <strong>Shutter options compared:</strong><br/>
        <strong>Accordion shutters</strong> — best option, fold away when not in use, deploy in seconds. Cost: $15–$25/sq ft installed.<br/>
        <strong>Roll-down shutters</strong> — excellent, can be motorized. Cost: $20–$35/sq ft installed.<br/>
        <strong>Panel shutters</strong> — good protection, must be stored and installed manually. Cost: $8–$15/sq ft.<br/>
        <strong>Plywood</strong> — last resort only. Not rated, labor intensive, and provides poor protection.
      </div>

      <p>
        The <strong>garage door is the most common structural failure point</strong> in a 
        hurricane. If your garage door is not wind-load rated, a bracing kit ($50–$300) 
        is one of the highest-ROI improvements you can make.
      </p>

      <!-- ── Section 4: Yard ── -->
      <h2 id="yard">4. Prepare Your Yard</h2>
      <p>
        In 100 mph winds, anything that isn't anchored becomes a projectile. A typical 
        backyard contains dozens of items that can shatter windows, damage roofs, or injure 
        people if left outside during a storm.
      </p>
      <ul class="checklist-preview">
        <li>Bring in all patio furniture, umbrellas, and cushions</li>
        <li>Secure or store grills — even heavy ones can be moved by hurricane winds</li>
        <li>Remove all decorative items, planters, and wind chimes</li>
        <li>Move firewood stacks away from the house or inside</li>
        <li>Trim dead branches before the season — don't wait until a storm is approaching</li>
        <li>Know which trees on your property are most likely to fall toward the house</li>
      </ul>

      <!-- ── Section 5: Emergency Supplies ── -->
      <h2 id="supplies">5. Build a Go-Bag and a Stay-Bag</h2>
      <p>
        Whether you shelter in place or evacuate, having 72 hours of supplies ready means 
        you're not making decisions under pressure when a storm is approaching. Most 
        evacuation failures happen because people weren't ready to leave quickly.
      </p>

      <div class="two-col">
        <div class="col-box">
          <h3>🏠 Stay-Bag (Shelter in Place)</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>2 weeks of water (1 gal/person/day)</li>
            <li>2 weeks of non-perishable food</li>
            <li>Battery-powered NOAA weather radio</li>
            <li>Flashlights and extra batteries</li>
            <li>First aid kit</li>
            <li>30-day supply of medications</li>
            <li>Manual can opener</li>
            <li>Cash in small bills</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="col-box">
          <h3>🚗 Go-Bag (Evacuation)</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>Critical documents in waterproof bag</li>
            <li>3 days of clothing per person</li>
            <li>Phone chargers and power bank</li>
            <li>Medications (30-day supply)</li>
            <li>Cash ($200–$500 minimum)</li>
            <li>Water and snacks for the drive</li>
            <li>Pet food, carriers, records</li>
            <li>N95 masks</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="product-grid" style="margin-top: 24px;">
        <ProductCard
          name="Midland ER310 Emergency Crank Weather Radio"
          asin="B00A4GE32E"
          price="$59"
          store="amazon"
          badge="Essential"
          desc="NOAA weather alerts, AM/FM, hand crank + solar charging. Works when cell networks and power are down. One of the most important items in any emergency kit."
        />
        <ProductCard
          name="Anker 737 Power Bank (PowerCore 24K)"
          asin="B09VPHVT2Z"
          price="$89"
          store="amazon"
          desc="24,000mAh — charges an iPhone 6+ times. Fast charging, two USB-A and one USB-C port. Keep it charged year-round."
        />
      </div>

      <p class="product-note">→ See our complete <a href="/emergency-kits">Emergency Kit Guide</a> for full recommendations and checklists.</p>

      <!-- ── 72-hour timeline ── -->
      <h2>The 72-Hour Pre-Storm Timeline</h2>
      <p>When a hurricane watch is issued for your area, here's exactly what to do and when.</p>

      <div class="timeline">
        <div class="timeline-item">
          <div class="timeline-marker">72 hrs</div>
          <div class="timeline-content">
            <strong>Make your evacuation decision</strong>
            <p>If you're in a mandatory evacuation zone, decide now. Waiting means gridlock. Fill your gas tank. Withdraw cash. Confirm your destination.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="timeline-item">
          <div class="timeline-marker">48 hrs</div>
          <div class="timeline-content">
            <strong>Secure the exterior</strong>
            <p>Install shutters or plywood. Bring all outdoor items inside. Trim any hanging branches. Charge all devices and power banks.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="timeline-item">
          <div class="timeline-marker">24 hrs</div>
          <div class="timeline-content">
            <strong>Prepare the interior</strong>
            <p>Move valuables to upper floors. Fill bathtub with water. Turn fridge to coldest setting. Unplug major appliances. Confirm go-bag is ready.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="timeline-item">
          <div class="timeline-marker">Storm</div>
          <div class="timeline-content">
            <strong>Shelter safely</strong>
            <p>Stay in an interior room on the lowest floor above flood level. Stay away from windows. Monitor NOAA radio.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="timeline-item">
          <div class="timeline-marker">After</div>
          <div class="timeline-content">
            <strong>Document before you repair</strong>
            <p>Photograph ALL damage before touching anything. Call your insurance company immediately. Watch for downed power lines — assume all are live.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- ── Checklist CTA ── -->
      <div class="checklist-cta" id="checklist">
        <div class="checklist-cta-inner">
          <div class="checklist-icon">🌀</div>
          <div>
            <h2>Download the Free Hurricane Home Prep Checklist</h2>
            <p>150+ action items organized by timeline — before the season, 72 hours out, day of, and after the storm. Enter your email and we'll send it instantly.</p>
            <form class="inline-email-form" name="hurricane-checklist" method="POST" data-netlify="true">
              <input type="hidden" name="form-name" value="hurricane-checklist" />
              <input type="email" name="email" placeholder="your@email.com" required />
              <button type="submit" class="btn btn-primary">Send Me the Checklist</button>
            </form>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

    </article>

    <!-- ── Right: Sidebar ── -->
    <aside class="sidebar">

      <div class="sidebar-card">
        <h3>Quick Links</h3>
        <a href="#power">⚡ Backup Power</a>
        <a href="#flood">🌊 Flood Protection</a>
        <a href="#windows">🪟 Windows & Shutters</a>
        <a href="#yard">🌳 Yard Prep</a>
        <a href="#supplies">🎒 Emergency Supplies</a>
        <a href="#checklist">✅ Free Checklist</a>
      </div>

      <div class="sidebar-card sidebar-alert">
        <h3>⚠️ Season Reminder</h3>
        <p>Hurricane season runs <strong>June 1 – November 30</strong>. Peak activity is August–September. Start preparing in April.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="sidebar-card">
        <h3>Related Guides</h3>
        <a href="/generators">Generator Buying Guide →</a>
        <a href="/flood-protection-products">Flood Protection Products →</a>
        <a href="/insurance">Hurricane Insurance Guide →</a>
        <a href="/emergency-kits">Emergency Kit Guide →</a>
        <a href="/backup-power">Backup Power Guide →</a>
      </div>

      <div class="sidebar-card">
        <h3>Know Your Zone</h3>
        <p>Find your hurricane evacuation zone before a storm forms — not after.</p>
        <a href="https://www.ready.gov/hurricanes" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="btn btn-primary" style="margin-top:12px; font-size:0.85rem; padding: 10px 16px;">
          Check Your Zone →
        </a>
      </div>

    </aside>

  </div>

</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .threat-hero {
    background: linear-gradient(135deg, #0a1f35 0%, #1B4F72 60%, #2874A6 100%);
    color: white;
    padding: 80px 0;
  }

  .threat-hero-inner { max-width: 700px; }

  .threat-eyebrow {
    font-size: 0.9rem;
    font-weight: 600;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: 0.1em;
    color: var(--light-sky);
    margin-bottom: 16px;
  }

  .threat-hero h1 { color: white; margin-bottom: 20px; }

  .threat-sub {
    font-size: 1.1rem;
    color: rgba(255,255,255,0.82);
    margin-bottom: 32px;
    line-height: 1.7;
  }

  .hero-ctas { display: flex; gap: 14px; flex-wrap: wrap; }

  /* Stats bar */
  .stats-bar {
    background: var(--navy);
    padding: 20px 0;
    border-bottom: 3px solid var(--orange);
  }

  .stats-grid {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(4, 1fr);
    gap: 20px;
    text-align: center;
  }

  .stat strong {
    display: block;
    color: var(--orange);
    font-size: 1rem;
    font-weight: 700;
  }

  .stat span {
    color: rgba(255,255,255,0.7);
    font-size: 0.78rem;
  }

  /* Content layout */
  .content-layout {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 1fr 300px;
    gap: 48px;
    padding-top: 56px;
    padding-bottom: 80px;
    align-items: start;
  }

  /* Article */
  .article-body h2 {
    margin-top: 48px;
    margin-bottom: 16px;
    color: var(--navy);
    padding-bottom: 8px;
    border-bottom: 2px solid var(--pale-blue);
  }

  .article-body h3 {
    margin-top: 28px;
    margin-bottom: 10px;
    color: var(--steel);
  }

  .article-body p { margin-bottom: 16px; line-height: 1.75; color: #333; }

  /* Risk cards */
  .risk-cards {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(2, 1fr);
    gap: 16px;
    margin: 28px 0;
  }

  .risk-card {
    background: var(--pale-blue);
    border-radius: 8px;
    padding: 20px;
    border-left: 4px solid var(--sky);
  }

  .risk-icon { font-size: 1.8rem; margin-bottom: 8px; }
  .risk-card h3 { font-size: 1rem; margin-top: 0; color: var(--navy); }
  .risk-card p { font-size: 0.85rem; margin-bottom: 0; color: var(--mid-gray); }

  /* Callouts */
  .callout {
    border-radius: 8px;
    padding: 16px 20px;
    margin: 24px 0;
    font-size: 0.9rem;
    line-height: 1.6;
  }

  .callout-tip     { background: #FEF9E7; border-left: 4px solid var(--amber); }
  .callout-warning { background: #FDEDEC; border-left: 4px solid #E74C3C; }
  .callout-info    { background: var(--pale-blue); border-left: 4px solid var(--sky); }

  /* Action steps */
  .action-steps { margin: 24px 0; display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 16px; }

  .action-step {
    display: flex;
    gap: 16px;
    align-items: flex-start;
  }

  .step-num {
    background: var(--sky);
    color: white;
    width: 32px;
    height: 32px;
    border-radius: 50%;
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    justify-content: center;
    font-weight: 700;
    font-size: 0.9rem;
    flex-shrink: 0;
  }

  .action-step strong { display: block; margin-bottom: 4px; color: var(--navy); }
  .action-step p { margin-bottom: 0; font-size: 0.88rem; color: #444; }

  /* Product sections */
  .product-section { margin: 32px 0; }
  .product-grid { display: grid; grid-template-columns: repeat(3, 1fr); gap: 20px; margin: 20px 0; }
  .product-note { font-size: 0.88rem; color: var(--mid-gray); margin-top: 12px; }

  /* Checklist */
  .checklist-preview {
    list-style: none;
    margin: 16px 0 24px;
    padding: 0;
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 8px;
  }

  .checklist-preview li {
    padding: 10px 14px 10px 40px;
    background: var(--off-white);
    border-radius: 6px;
    font-size: 0.9rem;
    position: relative;
  }

  .checklist-preview li::before {
    content: "☐";
    position: absolute;
    left: 14px;
    color: var(--sky);
    font-size: 1rem;
  }

  /* Two column */
  .two-col { display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; gap: 20px; margin: 20px 0; }

  .col-box {
    background: var(--off-white);
    border-radius: 8px;
    padding: 20px;
    border-top: 3px solid var(--sky);
  }

  .col-box h3 { font-size: 1rem; margin-bottom: 12px; color: var(--navy); }
  .col-box ul { list-style: none; padding: 0; }
  .col-box li { font-size: 0.85rem; padding: 5px 0; border-bottom: 1px solid #e5e5e5; color: #444; }
  .col-box li::before { content: "✓ "; color: var(--sky); font-weight: 700; }

  /* Timeline */
  .timeline { margin: 28px 0; display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 0; }

  .timeline-item {
    display: flex;
    gap: 20px;
    padding-bottom: 24px;
    position: relative;
  }

  .timeline-item:not(:last-child)::before {
    content: '';
    position: absolute;
    left: 44px;
    top: 36px;
    bottom: 0;
    width: 2px;
    background: var(--light-sky);
  }

  .timeline-marker {
    background: var(--navy);
    color: white;
    font-size: 0.72rem;
    font-weight: 700;
    padding: 6px 8px;
    border-radius: 6px;
    text-align: center;
    min-width: 52px;
    height: fit-content;
    flex-shrink: 0;
  }

  .timeline-content strong { display: block; margin-bottom: 4px; color: var(--navy); }
  .timeline-content p { font-size: 0.87rem; margin-bottom: 0; color: #555; }

  /* Checklist CTA */
  .checklist-cta {
    background: linear-gradient(135deg, var(--navy), var(--steel));
    border-radius: 12px;
    padding: 36px;
    margin: 48px 0;
    color: white;
  }

  .checklist-cta-inner { display: flex; gap: 24px; align-items: flex-start; }
  .checklist-icon { font-size: 3rem; flex-shrink: 0; }
  .checklist-cta h2 { color: white; font-size: 1.4rem; margin-bottom: 10px; margin-top: 0; border: none; padding: 0; }
  .checklist-cta p { color: rgba(255,255,255,0.8); font-size: 0.9rem; margin-bottom: 20px; }

  .inline-email-form { display: flex; gap: 10px; flex-wrap: wrap; }
  .inline-email-form input {
    padding: 10px 14px;
    border-radius: 6px;
    border: none;
    font-size: 0.9rem;
    min-width: 240px;
    font-family: var(--font);
  }

  /* Sidebar */
  .sidebar { position: sticky; top: 84px; display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 20px; }

  .sidebar-card {
    background: white;
    border: 1px solid #e2eaf2;
    border-radius: 10px;
    padding: 20px;
    box-shadow: 0 2px 8px rgba(0,0,0,0.05);
  }

  .sidebar-card h3 {
    font-size: 0.9rem;
    text-transform: uppercase;
